---
title: "Changes in CRAN submissions in the age of LLMs"
date: "2026-05-11"
description: |
  A brief look at data on CRAN submissions over time.
categories: [r]
editor:
  markdown:
    wrap: sentence
knitr:
  opts_chunk:
    echo: false
    warning: false
---

This is more data on CRAN submissions in 2026, to support and follow-up on the [DDSS blog](https://princeton-ddss.github.io/notes/cran-growth).


::: {.cell}

:::


New package submissions are taking off in 2026:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-new-packages-by-month-1.png){#fig-new-packages-by-month width=672}
:::
:::


Monthly package submissions, including updates, are up:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-all-submissions-by-month-1.png){#fig-all-submissions-by-month width=672}
:::
:::


Increases are relatively consistent across weeks:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-all-submissions-by-week-1.png){#fig-all-submissions-by-week width=672}
:::
:::


All package submissions are trending up in 2026:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-all-submissions-through-may7-1.png){#fig-all-submissions-through-may7 width=672}
:::
:::


New package submissions are way above expectations:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-new-packages-through-may7-1.png){#fig-new-packages-through-may7 width=672}
:::
:::


CRAN submissions from new authors have stayed relatively stable over time, with perhaps a dip in recent years:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-newcomer-authors-by-year-1.png){#fig-newcomer-authors-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


There's a big increase in solo-authored new packages in 2026:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-author-count-share-by-year-1.png){#fig-author-count-share-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


If the trend continues, single authored packages in 2026 would nearly double that of 2025:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-author-count-projected-by-year-1.png){#fig-author-count-projected-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


This is being driven by solo developers who have previously published packages on CRAN:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-author-profile-share-by-year-1.png){#fig-author-profile-share-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


If the trends continue, experienced developers would nearly hit the same number of packages as multi-author teams:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-author-profile-projected-by-year-1.png){#fig-author-profile-projected-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


There's been a small increase in the number of dependencies over time, especially from none to 1 or 2:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-hard-dependencies-by-year-1.png){#fig-hard-dependencies-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


Yet, data suggests packages are both becoming simpler and better documented, using some basic proxies:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-complexity-indicators-by-year-1.png){#fig-complexity-indicators-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


Packages are also including more suggested packages:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-suggested-dependencies-by-year-1.png){#fig-suggested-dependencies-by-year width=672}
:::
:::


Over the longer period of CRAN, we can see a change in contributions towards the `tidyverse` and `Rcpp` by looking at maintainers:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-cumulative-packages-by-maintainer-1.png){#fig-cumulative-packages-by-maintainer width=672}
:::
:::


Looking at authors, instead of just maintainers, highlights the RStudio/Posit contribution in the growing ecosystem:


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/fig-cumulative-packages-by-author-1.png){#fig-cumulative-packages-by-author width=672}
:::
:::
